<TITLE>Itzhak Bentov</TITLE>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="1" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Itzhak Bentov</REFEX></REF>
 (1923 - May 25, 1979) was a Czech born scientist, inventor, mystic and author. 
<REF MENTION="2" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 was an early exponent of what has come to be referred to as consciousness studies.
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="3" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Bentov</REFEX></REF>
 was born in Czechoslovakia and 
<REF MENTION="4" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="no_case" REG08-TYPE="empty" ENTITY="0">_</REFEX></REF>
 moved to Israel. In Israel, 
<REF MENTION="5" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 was part of the fledgling state's scientific unit, the Hemmed, where 
<REF MENTION="6" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 designed Israel's first rocket for the War of Independence. The Hemmed had to make improvised weapons as there was a world-wide embargo on selling weapons to the Jewish state.
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
After the war, 
<REF MENTION="7" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 moved to America where 
<REF MENTION="8" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 followed 
<REF MENTION="9" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">his</REFEX></REF>
 passion as an inventor. 
By profession 
<REF MENTION="10" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 was a mechanical engineer specialising in Biomedical Engineering and instrumentation. 
<REF MENTION="11" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 is credited with the invention of the remote controlled cardiac catheter (US Patent Sep., 1971 Bentov. )
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="12" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Bentov</REFEX></REF>
 was also an accomplished meditator.
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
By blending analytical knowledge and intuitive insight, 
<REF MENTION="13" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 was the first to develop what is now widely accepted as a holographic model of reality.
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="14" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">his</REFEX></REF>
 best known work is Stalking the Wild Pendulum: On the Mechanics of Consciousness (1977) in which 
<REF MENTION="15" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 described 
<REF MENTION="16" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">his</REFEX></REF>
 theory of The Continuous Big Bang Universe a form of Eternal return. (Its title was a play on that of 
<REF MENTION="1" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="1"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="1">Euell Gibbons'</REFEX></REF>
 popular 1962 book Stalking the Wild Asparagus.)
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="17" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Bentov</REFEX></REF>
 died in the American Airlines Flight 191 disaster at O'Hare International Airport in Chicago on May 25, 1979.
</PARAGRAPH>
